Introduction¶

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The orginal dataset contains 113,937 loans with 81 features. However, for my analysis, I created a sub file with only 104135 loans and 11 features after cleaning.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am more interested in finding out the category persons that take more loan and compare to their ability to pay back the loan ontime. This analysis is essential to credit companies as it helps in knowing their targeted customers and also know where money would not be lost unnecessarily.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think that the employment status, borrowerapr and income range would have effect on the result of this investigation. Also, the borrower rate seem to be a vital component that would affect my analysis.

Univariate Exploration¶

This section includes exploration of the dataset to get an insight into how the variables correlate with eachother.

In [17]:
#Checking the distribution of the credit grades
base_color = sb.color_palette()[2]
grade_order = loan_sub['creditgrade'].value_counts().index
sb.countplot(data=loan_sub, x = 'creditgrade', color = base_color, order = grade_order)
plt.xlabel('Credit Grade')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Available Credit Grades');

From the plot, it is obvious that a large proportion of the customers are on the C credit grade, followed by D with HR and E at the bottom.

In [18]:
#Taking a look at the distribution of loan amount

base_color=sb.color_palette()[2]

plt.hist(data = loan_sub, x = 'loanoriginalamount', color=base_color,bins = bins);
plt.xlabel('Loan Original Amount')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Distribution Of Loan Original Amount');

The graph tends towards the left, showing that most loans collected are less than 30000.

In [24]:
#Plotting the borrower rate and borrow apr to see if there is a significant difference
base_color = sb.color_palette()[2]
plt.figure(figsize = (12,6))

plt.subplot(1,2,1)
bins= np.arange(0, loan_sub['borrowerrate'].max()+0.05, 0.05)
plt.hist(data =loan_sub, x = 'borrowerrate', color = base_color, bins=bins)
plt.xticks(rotation = 45)
plt.xlabel('Borrower Rate')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Distribution of Borrower Rate');

plt.subplot(1,2,2)
bins= np.arange(0, loan_sub['borrowerapr'].max()+0.05, 0.05)
plt.hist(data =loan_sub, x= 'borrowerapr', color = base_color, bins = bins)
plt.xticks(rotation = 45)
plt.xlabel('Borrower APR')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.ylim(0, 25000)
plt.title('Distribution of Borrower APR');

Despite the fact that there are few loans beyond 0.4, the borrower apr still has quite some loans more than the borrower rate.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

From the distribution, a vast percentage of the loan-takers are employed and their stated monthly income within the range of 5000 - 15,000 dollars, thus it made sense that the loans were usually paid on time as most of the loan taken were less than 30,000 dollars. Regarding transformations, on the loan status, I had to group together all the Past Due together and still was less than the defaulted value.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I removed duplicates and null values in order to get a clear view of the distribution. On the loan original amount, most loans were less than 30,000 dollars and just a bit at 35,000 dollars which can be viewed as an outlier.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

In terms of apr and loan amount, increase in the loan amount leads to a decrease in apr, thus, they are negatively correlated.

Multivariate Exploration¶

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The stated monthly income is negatively correlated to the loan original amount. The borrower apr is also inversely related to the loan orginal amount.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

It was surprising to see that despite the loan term of 36 months having the higher percentage, the 60months term had higher loan amount. Also, the loan term of 12months have higher stated monthly income, yet has a larger ratio of defaulted payments even when the loan amounts are not as high as those of 60months and 36months.
